            <!-- Left Content -->
            <div class="content-left">
              <!-- Introduction Section -->
              <div class="content-section">
                <h2>Eligibility Criteria for IELTS</h2>
                <p>The International English Language Testing System (IELTS) is a globally recognized English proficiency test that measures the candidate’s ability to use English in their daily life across the four skills of listening, writing, reading, and speaking. This test is designed to meet the needs of those wishing to improve their English language proficiency and obtain recognition for their level of education.</p>
                <p>There are no particular eligibility criteria for IELTS, the only IELTS eligibility criteria prescribed by IDP require candidates to be at least 16 years of age to be able to register for the IELTS exam 2024. To understand more about IELTS Eligibility please read on!</p>
              </div>
    
              <!-- Eligibility Criteria Section -->
              <div class="content-section">
                <h2>IELTS Eligibility Criteria</h2>
                <div class="highlight-box">
                  <table>
                    <thead>
                      <tr>
                        <th>Criteria</th>
                        <th>Details</th>
                      </tr>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
                      <tr>
                        <td>Minimum age</td>
                        <td>16 years old.</td>
                      </tr>
                      <tr>
                        <td>Educational requirement</td>
                        <td>No specific educational qualifications are needed.</td>
                      </tr>
                      <tr>
                        <td>Purpose of IELTS</td>
                        <td>Accepted for study, migration, and work purposes in English-speaking countries.</td>
                      </tr>
                      <tr>
                        <td>Test types</td>
                        <td>Academic (for higher education and professional registration) and General Training (for migration and work).</td>
                      </tr>
                      <tr>
                        <td>Identification document</td>
                        <td>Valid passport or national ID (based on country and test center requirements).</td>
                      </tr>
                      <tr>
                        <td>Band score</td>
                        <td>Graded on a scale from 0 to 9 for each section and overall score.</td>
                      </tr>
                    </tbody>
                  </table>
                </div>
              </div>
    
              <!-- Age Requirements Section -->
              <div class="content-section">
                <h2>1. Age Requirements</h2>
                <p><strong>Minimum Age:</strong> Candidates have to be a minimum of 16 years old for the IELTS test. This age condition safeguards both the practicality of the test and the finer language intellect and emotional stability that is compulsory for accomplishing the test.</p>
                <p><strong>Upper Age Limit:</strong> There is no upper age limit, meaning individuals of any age above 16 are eligible to take the exam if they meet other criteria.</p>
              </div>
    
              <!-- Educational Qualifications Section -->
              <div class="content-section">
                <h2>2. Educational Qualifications</h2>
                <p>IELTS does not mandate any specific educational background or qualification, making it accessible to a wide range of applicants. Such an approach is highly useful for candidates with nontraditional or non-prestigious backgrounds in education.</p>
              </div>
    
              <!-- Purpose of the Exam Section -->
              <div class="content-section">
                <h2>3. Purpose of the Exam</h2>
                <p>The IELTS is intended for those who wish to study, work, or migrate to another country where the English language is used. IELTS is a requirement in many institutions within 140 countries like the USA, Australia, UK, Canada, Ireland, New Zealand, and so on.</p>
                <p>The IELTS offers two main formats to suit different purposes:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li><strong>Academic:</strong> Especially for candidates who want to apply for higher learning institutions or a professional body.</li>
                  <li><strong>General Training:</strong> Targeting the job seekers looking for immigration and overall employment.</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
    
              <!-- Required Identification Documents Section -->
              <div class="content-section">
                <h2>4. Required Identification Documents</h2>
                <p>Candidates must have the following list of documents for identification:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>A valid passport</li>
                  <li>A national ID card</li>
                  <li>Two recent identical passport-sized photographs</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
    
              <!-- IELTS Eligibility by Country Section -->
              <div class="content-section">
                <h2>IELTS Eligibility by Country</h2>
                <div class="highlight-box">
                  <table>
                    <thead>
                      <tr>
                        <th>Country</th>
                        <th>Student</th>
                        <th>Work</th>
                      </tr>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
                      <tr>
                        <td>United Kingdom</td>
                        <td>University level – between 5.5 and 6.5<br>Below the university level – between 4.0 and 5.0</td>
                        <td>4.0 to 5.0</td>
                      </tr>
                      <tr>
                        <td>United States</td>
                        <td>Each school sets its requirements.</td>
                        <td>Generally, the score ranges from 5.5 to higher</td>
                      </tr>
                      <tr>
                        <td>Canada</td>
                        <td>No set score.</td>
                        <td>4.0 to 6.0</td>
                      </tr>
                      <tr>
                        <td>Australia</td>
                        <td>6.0 to 7.0</td>
                        <td>Minimum 6</td>
                      </tr>
                      <tr>
                        <td>Germany</td>
                        <td>5.5 to 6.5</td>
                        <td>No set score</td>
                      </tr>
                    </tbody>
                  </table>
                </div>
              </div>
    
              <!-- Score Eligibility Requirement Section -->
              <div class="content-section">
                <h2>Score Eligibility Requirement for IELTS</h2>
                <p>The required IELTS score depends on why you are taking the test, such as applying to a university or for a visa.</p>
                <div class="highlight-box">
                  <table>
                    <thead>
                      <tr>
                        <th>IELTS Purpose</th>
                        <th>Features</th>
                        <th>Required IELTS Score</th>
                      </tr>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
                      <tr>
                        <td>Undergraduate Programs</td>
                        <td>Requirements vary by country and institution; some may have specific minimums for each test section (Listening, Reading, Writing, Speaking).</td>
                        <td>6.0 to 6.5 overall</td>
                      </tr>
                      <tr>
                        <td>Graduate Programs</td>
                        <td>Many programs require a minimum of 6.5 in each section; some top universities or specialized programs may ask for 7.0 or higher.</td>
                        <td>6.5 to 7.0 overall</td>
                      </tr>
                      <tr>
                        <td>Visa Applications</td>
                        <td>For visas, particularly work and skilled visas, minimum requirements often align with university standards; and may require 6.5 in each section.</td>
                        <td>6.0 to 6.5 overall</td>
                      </tr>
                      <tr>
                        <td>Preparatory/Foundation Courses</td>
                        <td>Some foundation programs accept lower scores to accommodate students working on language skills before beginning their degree programs.</td>
                        <td>4.0 to 5.5 overall</td>
                      </tr>
                      <tr>
                        <td>Specific Programs/Countries</td>
                        <td>Check each institution’s specific requirements as countries or institutions may have unique standards for minimum scores in each section or overall.</td>
                        <td>No set score. Will vary.</td>
                      </tr>
                    </tbody>
                  </table>
                </div>
              </div>
    
              <!-- FAQs Section -->
              <div class="content-section">
                <h2>Frequently Asked Questions (FAQs)</h2>
                <div class="highlight-box">
                  <h3>Can I appear for the IELTS exam after class 10 boards?</h3>
                  <p>Anyone can take the IELTS exam, regardless of their educational qualification. You can take the test as long as you feel comfortable with English and need it for your studies or career. However, you must be at least 16 years old to take the exam.</p>
                  <h3>How can I practice for the IELTS exam?</h3>
                  <p>To get ready for the IELTS test, you can take free practice tests on the British Council and IDP websites. These resources can help you improve your skills in listening, reading, writing, and speaking by giving you example questions and answers.</p>
                  <h3>How many times can I appear for IELTS?</h3>
                  <p>You can take the IELTS exam as many times as you like. It’s offered very frequently, up to 48 times a year.</p>
                  <h3>Is 7.0 A good IELTS score?</h3>
                  <p>A score of 7.0 is generally considered a good result and usually meets the requirements for most universities and visa applications. It shows that the person has a good understanding of the English language.</p>
                  <h3>How many years is IELTS valid?</h3>
                  <p>Your IELTS score is usually good for two years from the day you take the test. But, some schools and organizations might have their own rules about how long it’s valid.</p>
                </div>
              </div>
